L. A manuscript of the end ol the twelsth, or beginning of the thirteenth century, now in the Public Library of the University of Cam· bridge, marked F. f. i. 27. Itis a handsome vo· lume, written in double columns, upon vellum, appears once to have belonged to the monks of Barbam, (see this Introduction, ς 15, note ¹,) and is the only ancient copy which contains both Prologues. It formed, as has already . been remarked, the basis of Gale's text3 and is the only copy which prefixes to the history a series of Capitula, which contain internal evidence either of forgery or interpolation. These have in this edition been thrown into an Appendix. This manuscript also contains the following verses, which may perhaps be worth preserving, as well as two extracts from some short chronological memoranda.
